{"text": " It's currently citrus season here in South Florida, so today we're going to pick some of these delicious fruits and make a homemade marmalade. One of the most common types of wild citrus you'll find down here in South Florida are these little orange fruits called Kalamundins. And if you look up in this tree right here, you can see that there's quite a few of them up there. On their own, these fruits can be pretty sour. The inside is extremely sour, and the outside has a little bit of sweetness in the peel. Hmm. But combined with a little bit of sugar, these fruits are absolutely delicious in a marmalade. This is a good little clump right here. Check out these. This one's huge. Back in the kitchen, I washed all the Kalamundins just to make sure that they were nice and clean, and then I cut them up and started making the marmalade. For the entire recipe, be sure to check my full-length YouTube video, which is now up. Once it was done cooking, I added it to jars and set it in the fridge so that it could chill and set up overnight. It's now the next morning, so it's time to check on the marmalade and see how it looks. Overnight, as it's set up in the fridge, you can see that it now has the nice jam-like consistency that we're looking for. It looks absolutely amazing, but now it's time to see how it tastes. Mmm, mmm, mmm. This is a 10 out of 10. I'm not even kidding when I say I could absolutely eat this every single day. Until next time, get outside and see what you can find. Mmm, mmm, mmm.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 3.44, "text": " It's currently citrus season here in South Florida, so today we're going to pick some", "tokens": [50364, 467, 311, 4362, 37217, 3196, 510, 294, 4242, 9117, 11, 370, 965, 321, 434, 516, 281, 1888, 512, 50536], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17758007538624299, "compression_ratio": 1.8130563798219586, "no_speech_prob": 0.00506477989256382}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 3.44, "end": 6.48, "text":